#compdef ar5iv
# ============================================================================
# ar5iv - HTML5 article server for arXiv.org
#          papers converted from LaTeX via
#          latexml (Rust, MIT)
#
# Author : Deyan Ginev (dginev)
# Upstream: https://github.com/dginev/ar5iv
# crates : ar5iv (binary: ar5iv)
#
# `ar5iv` is the Rust HTTP server powering
# ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org - the production service
# that converts arXiv.org's daily LaTeX paper
# uploads into accessible HTML5 articles. The
# conversion is performed offline via LaTeXML
# (Bruce Miller's TeX-to-HTML5 toolchain); ar5iv
# is the Rocket-based HTTP server that:
#   - Reads pre-converted paper archives
#     (.zip files) from a configured paper-root
#     directory (typically NFS-mounted)
#   - Extracts HTML + image + CSS assets from
#     the ZIP via zip-rs (the canonical Rust
#     ZIP library)
#   - Caches extracted content in Redis (via
#     rocket_db_pools::deadpool_redis)
#   - Serves the HTML5 articles at /html/<id>
#     + assets at /html/<id>/assets/<filename>
#   - Falls back to redirecting to arxiv.org/
#     abs/<id> when a paper hasn't been
#     converted yet
#
# ar5iv is part of the broader LaTeXML/arXiv-vanity
# ecosystem of accessibility tooling. It enables:
#   - Screen-reader-accessible arXiv papers
#   - Reflowable text on mobile devices (vs PDF's
#     fixed pixel layout)
#   - MathJax-rendered equations (vs PDF's
#     baked-in font rendering)
#   - Linkable hyperlinks to references, figures,
#     equations
#
# Use cases:
#   - Hosting ar5iv-style article servers for
#     academic communities (production deployment
#     of the actual ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org service)
#   - Mirror ar5iv content for offline / air-
#     gapped research environments
#   - Self-hosted accessibility-optimized arxiv
#     reading service
#
# Usage:
#   ar5iv [rocket-options]
#
# Rocket-based configuration is primarily via
# `Rocket.toml` config file + ROCKET_* environment
# variables (no traditional CLI flags). The Rocket
# launcher reads:
#   - `Rocket.toml` from the binary's cwd (or
#     ROCKET_CONFIG-pointed path)
#   - Environment variables (ROCKET_PORT,
#     ROCKET_ADDRESS, ROCKET_WORKERS, etc.)
#   - Per-profile config sections ([global],
#     [default], [debug], [release])
#
# Common Rocket environment variables:
#   ROCKET_PORT                   - HTTP listen
#                                    port (default
#                                    8000)
#   ROCKET_ADDRESS                - HTTP listen
#                                    address
#                                    (default
#                                    127.0.0.1)
#   ROCKET_WORKERS                - number of
#                                    Tokio worker
#                                    threads
#                                    (default
#                                    cpus*2)
#   ROCKET_LOG_LEVEL              - log level
#                                    (off/critical
#                                    /normal/
#                                    debug)
#   ROCKET_PROFILE                - profile to
#                                    use (default
#                                    /debug/
#                                    release)
#   ROCKET_CONFIG                 - path to
#                                    Rocket.toml
#                                    config file
#   ROCKET_KEEP_ALIVE             - HTTP keep-
#                                    alive timeout
#                                    (default
#                                    5s)
#   ROCKET_LIMITS                 - request size
#                                    limits
#                                    (form/data/
#                                    json sub-keys)
#   ROCKET_TEMPLATE_DIR           - template
#                                    directory
#                                    (default
#                                    `templates/`)
#   ROCKET_DATABASES              - per-database
#                                    config (TOML
#                                    nested values)
#
# Application-specific environment variables:
#   AR5IV_PAPERS_ROOT_DIR         - path to the
#                                    arxiv paper
#                                    archive root
#                                    (where the
#                                    .zip files
#                                    live)
#   REDIS_URL                     - Redis cache
#                                    URL (default
#                                    redis://
#                                    127.0.0.1)
#
# Standard Rocket CLI flags (parsed by the
# rocket launcher):
#   --help                       - print Rocket
#                                    help
#
# Example invocation:
#   ROCKET_PORT=8080 \
#   ROCKET_LOG_LEVEL=normal \
#   AR5IV_PAPERS_ROOT_DIR=/data/arxmliv/ \
#   ar5iv
#
# Companion binary in the same crate:
#   cache_adjacency_map           - separate
#                                    binary
#                                    (declared
#                                    as `[[bin]]`
#                                    in Cargo.toml)
#                                    that walks
#                                    AR5IV_PAPERS_ROOT_DIR
#                                    + populates
#                                    the Redis
#                                    `paper_order`
#                                    key with
#                                    next/prev
#                                    paper links
#                                    for sequential
#                                    browsing
#
# Rocket.toml example for ar5iv:
#   [global]
#   template_dir = "templates/"
#   workers = 32
#   keep_alive = 15
#   limits = { forms = 32768 }
#
#   [default.databases.memdb]
#   url = "redis://127.0.0.1"
#   min_connections = 8
#   max_connections = 1024
#   connect_timeout = 3
#   idle_timeout = 120
#
# The zip lane is built on `zip = "8.1"` (declared
# verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct
# dep, imported as `use zip::ZipArchive;` in
# src/assemble_asset.rs line 7, used at line 44+
# in the paper-archive extraction path:
# `ZipArchive::new(BufReader::new(File::open(
# paper_path)?))` to extract individual files
# from arxiv paper .zip archives on each HTTP
# request), the canonical Rust ZIP archive
# library by the zip-rs maintainers - github.com/
# zip-rs/zip2 (formerly github.com/zip-rs/zip).
#
# zip-rs/zip2 is the de-facto canonical Rust ZIP
# archive library:
#   - Implements the PKZIP / APPNOTE.txt format
#     specification
#   - Supports deflate / deflate64 / bzip2 /
#     zstd / xz compression methods (configurable
#     via cargo features)
#   - Streaming + random-access read APIs
#   - Builder-style write API
#   - ZIP64 support for archives larger than
#     4 GiB / 65,535 entries
#   - Encrypted ZIP support (traditional PKWare
#     + AES-256)
#   - Symlink + special-file support
#   - Pure Rust (no C dependencies)
#
# zip-rs's distinguishing position vs
# alternatives:
#   - zip-rs/zip2: canonical sync ZIP; THIS AXIS;
#     recent v8 release added bzip2 + zstd
#   - Majored/rs-async-zip: async ZIP for
#     tokio + futures; separate codebase
#   - thbar/zip-extract: thin wrapper around
#     zip-rs for simple extraction use cases
#
# zip-rs's maintainer governance:
#   - Originally by Mathijs van de Nes + the
#     mvdnes/zip-rs project (2014-2020)
#   - Forked + community-maintained as zip-rs/
#     zip in 2020
#   - Currently maintained by Plecra + the
#     zip-rs/zip2 maintainer team
#   - The v8 version (2024+) consolidates the
#     codebase + adds modern compression backends
#
# This is the *community-org-maintained
# canonical* pattern - the library was
# originally a single-author project but
# transitioned to multi-maintainer governance as
# adoption grew. Similar to:
#   - svg/svgo (Node, Axis 264): single-author
#     -> multi-maintainer org
#   - axios/axios (Node, Axis 265): single-
#     author -> contributor team
#   - linebender/resvg (Rust, Axis 264): single-
#     author -> Linebender Foundation
#
# Cross-language ZIP library landscape:
#   - Rust: zip-rs/zip2 (THIS AXIS)
#   - Go: archive/zip (stdlib) + mholt/archives
#     (wrapper)
#   - Python: stdlib zipfile + py7zr (7-zip
#     extension)
#   - Java: java.util.zip + Apache Commons
#     Compress
#   - C: minizip + libzip + zlib's ZIP support
#
# ZIP is one of the most-implemented archive
# formats due to its 1989 origin (PKZIP) + the
# format's relative simplicity (central directory
# at EOF + per-entry local file headers). Every
# language ecosystem has at least one canonical
# implementation.
#
# ar5iv uses zip-rs in src/assemble_asset.rs's
# `fetch_zip` function:
#   ```rust
#   use zip::ZipArchive;
#
#   let zipf = File::open(paper_path)?;
#   let reader = BufReader::new(zipf);
#   let mut zip = ZipArchive::new(reader)?;
#
#   // Iterate + extract specific files
#   for i in 0..zip.len() {
#     let mut file = zip.by_index(i)?;
#     if file.name() == requested_name {
#       let mut content = Vec::new();
#       file.read_to_end(&mut content)?;
#       return Ok(content);
#     }
#   }
#   ```
# This is wrapped in `spawn_blocking` (tokio's
# OS-thread offload) because zip-rs uses
# synchronous I/O; the async Rocket runtime
# offloads the blocking ZIP extraction to a
# dedicated thread pool.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 267 :: ZIP archive libraries (PKZIP/
#              APPNOTE.txt format parsing +
#              writing with deflate/bzip2/zstd
#              compression backends)
# Round 1499 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 267
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : zip-rs/zip2                  - Plecra +
#                                              zip-rs
#                                              maintainer
#                                              team's
#                                              canonical
#                                              Rust ZIP
#                                              library;
#                                              v8 added
#                                              bzip2 +
#                                              zstd
#                                              backends
#   Go      : archive/zip (stdlib) OR        - Go's
#             mholt/archives (wrapping it)    bundled
#                                              archive/zip;
#                                              mholt/
#                                              archives
#                                              is the
#                                              canonical
#                                              wrapper
#                                              for
#                                              format
#                                              abstraction
#   TS/Node : Stuk/jszip                     - Stuart
#                                              Knightley's
#                                              canonical
#                                              Node ZIP
#                                              library;
#                                              45,000,000+
#                                              weekly npm
#                                              downloads;
#                                              browser +
#                                              Node
#                                              isomorphic
#
# ZIP is a *spec-bound* axis - the PKWARE
# APPNOTE.txt format specification + ZIP64
# extension + the various compression-method
# encodings (deflate via RFC 1951 + bzip2 +
# LZMA + zstd) define the byte-for-byte archive
# format. Compliant implementations produce +
# consume byte-identical archives modulo:
#   - Compression-method selection (deflate is
#     universal; bzip2/zstd/lzma are optional)
#   - Encryption support (traditional PKWare
#     XOR + AES-256)
#   - Extra field encoding (per-entry extension
#     fields with vendor-defined semantics)
#   - File mode/permission representation (Unix
#     vs DOS attribute fields)
#   - Timestamp precision (DOS time: 2-second
#     granularity; ZIP extension: nanosecond
#     precision)
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - zip-rs/zip2 (Rust): pure-Rust; multi-
#     compression-backend; sync API (with async
#     variant in separate crate)
#   - archive/zip (Go): bundled stdlib; minimal
#     but complete deflate support
#   - jszip (Node): isomorphic browser + Node;
#     45M+ weekly npm downloads; promise-based
#     API
#
# Cross-language interop at the archive byte
# level - the same .zip file can be read +
# written by all three libraries (with the
# encryption/extra-field/timestamp caveats
# above).
#
# Axis 267 opens with the Rust slot at zip-rs/
# zip2 (the current canonical iteration of the
# Rust ZIP library family). Subsequent rounds
# will visit the Go (archive/zip + mholt/
# archives) + TS/Node (Stuk/jszip) canonicals.
#
# Notable pattern continuity from Axis 266 (TAR)
# to Axis 267 (ZIP):
#   - Both axes have Rust individual-authored
#     canonical (tar-rs by Crichton + zip-rs by
#     Plecra/maintainer team)
#   - Both axes have Go language-as-canonical-
#     provider stdlib (archive/tar + archive/zip,
#     both shipped with Go 1.0)
#   - Both axes have Node infrastructure-tier
#     canonicals (Schlueter's node-tar +
#     Knightley's jszip)
#
# This parallel pattern reflects the ecosystem-
# governance norms in each language - Rust's
# individual-authorship culture, Go's stdlib-
# first culture, and Node's infrastructure-via-
# tutorial-ecosystem culture each manifest
# consistently across format-handling library
# axes.
# ============================================================================

_ar5iv() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)--help[print Rocket help]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version]'
}

_ar5iv "$@"
